    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="hav.00003.002_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <div1 type="letter">
                <p> Thanks for the invitation to write <choice>
                        <abbr>ab't</abbr>
                        <expan>about</expan>
                    </choice> Whittier&#8212;<choice>
                        <abbr>wh</abbr>
                        <expan>which</expan>
                    </choice> I will if the spirit moves me&#8212;I cannot tell decidedly at this
                    moment, but will try&#8212;cannot tell either what extent the piece (if any)
                    will be, nor price&#8212; </p>
                <note type="authorial" place="bottom">(Price <lb/>&#36;20)</note>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Walt Whitman</signed>
                </closer>
                <dateline><date when="1887-12-12">Dec 12 '87</date></dateline>

            </div1>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="hav.00003.001_large.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <div1 type="enclosure">
                <note type="authorial" place="top">
                    <p><handShift rend="printed"/>WALT WHITMAN'S PRAISE.</p>
                    <p>HE DEDICATES A POEM TO HIS FRIEND, SPECIALLY WRITTEN FOR THE HERALD.</p>
                    <p>AS THE GREEKS SIGNAL FLAME.</p>
                    <p><hi rend="italic">(For Whittier's Eightieth Birthday, December 17,
                            1887.)</hi></p>
                    <p/>
                    <lg type="linegroup">
                        <l>As the Greek's signal flame, by antique records told</l>
                        <l><seg>Tally of many a hard strain'd battle, struggle,</seg>
                            <seg>year&#8212;triumphant only at the last),</seg></l>
                        <l>Rose from the hilltop, like applause and glory,</l>
                        <l>Welcoming in fame some special veteran, hero,</l>
                        <l>With rosy tinge reddening the land he'd served,</l>
                        <l>So I aloft from Mannahatta's ship fringed shore,</l>
                        <l>Lift high a kindled brand for thee, Old Poet.</l>
                    </lg>
                    <l><hi rend="left">WALT WHITMAN.</hi></l>
                </note>
            </div1>
            <div1 type="enclosure">
                <opener>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="printed"/><gap reason="covered" quantity="1"
                            unit="chars"/>Herald,</name>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="printed"/>New York,</name>
                    <dateline><date when="1887-12-11"><handShift rend="manuscript"/>Dec 11,
                                <handShift rend="printed"/>188<handShift rend="manuscript"
                            />7,</date></dateline>
                    <salute rend="right">Dear Mr. Browning:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p> Please go over personally to see Walt Whitman and ask him to write an ode about
                    the good old Poet John Greenleaf Whittier. It must be ready to send us by
                    messenger or by telegraph <hi rend="underline">on Wednesday</hi> afternoon or
                    evening. (If by telegraph, insert the word paragraph at the end of each line to
                    ensure accuracy.) </p>
                <p> Tell the good old man Whitman, from Mr Bennett, that Mr Bennett will be glad to
                    pay him well for a brief ode on the subject. Then let me know when you send the
                    lines what he expects, and I will see that a check is sent him </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute rend="center">Sincerely,</salute>
                    <signed rend="right">Julius Chambers</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>

        </body>
